{Responding to preempts is easy. You don't count points, you just count tricks. Assume partner for 6 tricks and add yours to see how high to go (or not go).

Here, with three Aces and a possible \S ruff you raise to game.

South would play 4\H.

Click 

North plays 4\H. West leads the \DK.

Things look grim. The defense has exposed your \D losers already and those two \S losers seem pretty obvious also. If you are to make this contract you must do so before you lose the lead. That means you must establish the \C suit <b>NOW</b>.

Win the \DA, play \CA and ruff the \C2 with a high trump. Play a \H to the \H10 and ruff the \C4 with a high trump. Play a \H to the \HJ and ruff the \C8 with a high trump. Play a \H to the \HA and discard a loser on the good \C9.

It took a 4-3 \C split to make this contract. 

Fortunately that occurs a high percentage of the time. In any case, there was no other hope.}
[Play "W"]DK

